THE GIST OF THE PROPOSITION IS AS FOLLOWS:
9
10
This measure adds a new Section 44 to Article 10 of the Oklahoma
10
11
Constitution, creating the Taxpayer’s Bill of Rights. This
11
12
measure restrains the growth of government spending through
12
13
limitations on levy increases and taxpayer refunds. The measure
13
14
authorizes citizens to bring suit to enforce the limitations.
14
15
The measure requires voter approval before the issuance of new
15
16
debt and measures to increase revenue, and authorizes voters to
16
17
suspend the voter approval requirements for a certain period.
17
18
Notices on ballot elections and information pertaining to dates,
18
19
costs of revenue raising measures, costs for the issuance of
19
20
debt, spending amounts, and certain other information are
20
21
required to be sent to registered voters at least thirty days
21
22
before elections. The measure requires taxpayer refunds to be
22
23
issued if tax levies or spending exceed estimates. The measure
23
24
requires the disclosure of tax increases and extensions to be
24
Req. No. 2578 Page 11

1
included in ballot titles. The measure requires voter approval
1
2
for all measures that directly or indirectly increase revenue or
2
3
extend existing revenue-raising measures and measures to
3
4
increase debt. The measure requires political subdivisions to
4
5
reserve emergency funds. The measure provides for the levy of
5
6
emergency taxes with a super majority approval of the
6
7
Legislature or local governing bodies, which shall later be
7
8
approved by voters. The measure limits annual spending and
8
9
property tax increases based on inflation and population
9
10
increases, with certain exceptions, and, if the limits are
10
11
exceeded, requires the excess to be refunded to the taxpayer.
11
12
The measure prohibits any new tax or increases to any existing
12
13
tax on the transfer of property. The measure prohibits the levy
13
14
